{"questionId":"19202","questionHtml":"<p>By differentiating the series in part (a), show that the Maclaurin series for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp;.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong style=\"font-style:italic;\">A1</strong><em><strong>A</strong><strong>1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>attempts to expand the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>RHS</mtext></math>&nbsp;up to and including the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;term&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><em><strong>[4 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19202","referenceCode":"20N.2.AHL.TZ0.F_5b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By differentiating the series in part (a), show that the Maclaurin series for sin(ln(1+x)) is x-12x2+16x3+… .","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 4]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.19—Maclaurin series"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}